{"title_page": "Long-term effects of global warming", "text_new": "{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:Sea level rise projections for the 21st century.png|thumb|Sea level rise projections for the 21st century.]]\n:''See also [[Effects of global warming]]. The focus of this article is on the effects beyond 2100.''\n\nThere are expected to be various '''long-term effects of global warming'''. Most discussion and research, including that by the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (IPCC) reports, concentrates on the effects of [[global warming]] up to 2100, with only an outline of the effects beyond this.\n\n==Ice loss and sea level rise==\n[[File:Larsen B collapse.jpg|thumb|The collapse of [[Larsen Ice Shelf|Larsen B Shelf]], showing the diminishing extent of the shelf from 1998 to 2002]]\n{{Main|Arctic shrinkage}}\n\n[[Meltwater]] from melting [[ice sheet]]s and [[Retreat of glaciers since 1850|glacier retreat]] contributes to a rise in the [[future sea level]].<ref name=\"TAR 11.3\" />\n\n===Antarctica===\nConcern has been expressed about the stability of the [[West Antarctic ice sheet]] (WAIS). In 2002 [[David Vaughan (scientist)|Vaughan]] & Spouge argued that the \"WAIS most likely will not collapse in the next few centuries.\"<ref>{{Cite journal| first1 = D. G.| first2 = J. R. | journal = Climatic Change | volume = 52| last1 = Vaughan | pages = 65\u201300 | year = 2002 | doi = 10.1023/A:1013038920600|title=Risk Estimation of Collapse of the West Antarctic Ice Sheet| last2 =    Spouge}}</ref>  In an inaugural article for members of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]] elected in 2005, [[Timothy Lenton]] and others suggest that a collapse of the West Antarctic ice sheet could occur within a millennium. Specifically, they state \"Although the timescale is highly uncertain, a qualitative WAIS change could occur within this millennium, with collapse within 300 years being a worst-case scenario. Rapid sea-level rise (greater than 1 m per century) is more likely to come from the WAIS than from the [[Greenland ice sheet]].\".<ref name=lenton>{{Cite journal | last1 = Lenton | first1 = T. M. | last2 = Held | first2 = H. | last3 = Kriegler | first3 = E. | last4 = Hall | first4 = J. W. | last5 = Lucht | first5 = W. | last6 = Rahmstorf | first6 = S. | last7 = Schellnhuber | first7 = H. J. | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0705414105 | title = Inaugural Article: Tipping elements in the Earth's climate system | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume = 105 | issue = 6 | pages = 1786\u20131793 | year = 2008 | pmid =  18258748| pmc = 2538841| bibcode=2008PNAS..105.1786L}}</ref> A study in 2015 found that assuming cumulative fossil fuel emissions of 10&nbsp;000 gigatonnes of carbon, the Antarctic Ice Sheet could melt completely over the following millennia, contributing 58 m to global sea-level rise, and 30 m within the first 1000 years.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Winkelmann | first1 = Ricarda | last2 = Levermann | first2 = Anders | last3 = Ridgwell | first3 = Andy | last4 = Caldeira | first4 = Ken | year = 2015 | title = Combustion of available fossil fuel resources sufficient to eliminate the Antarctic Ice Sheet | url = | journal = Science Advances | volume = 1 | issue = 8| page = e1500589 | doi = 10.1126/sciadv.1500589 | pmid = 26601273 | pmc = 4643791 | bibcode = 2015SciA....1E0589W }}</ref>\n\n===Greenland===\n[[Greenland ice sheet|Greenland's ice sheet]] contains enough [[fresh water]] as ice to raise sea level worldwide by {{convert|7|m|ft|0}}.<ref name=\"TAR 11.3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.grida.no/climate/ipcc_tar/wg1/412.htm#tab113 |title=Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis |publisher=[[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] |format=Table 11.3 |date=2001-02-16 |accessdate=2007-12-24}}</ref>  Greenland may become warm enough by 2100 to begin an almost complete melt over more than 1,000 years.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Gregory JM |authorlink=Jonathan M. Gregory |author2=Huybrechts P |author3=Raper SC |title=Climatology: threatened loss of the Greenland ice-sheet |journal=Nature |volume=428 |issue=6983 |pages=616 |date=April 2004 |pmid=15071587 |doi=10.1038/428616a |url=http://homepages.vub.ac.be/~phuybrec/pdf/Nature.Green.2004.pdf |quote=The Greenland ice-sheet would melt faster in a warmer climate and is likely to be eliminated \u2014 except for residual glaciers in the mountains \u2014 if the annual average temperature in Greenland increases by more than about 3 \u00b0C. This would raise the global average sea-level by 7 metres over a period of 1000 years or more. We show here that concentrations of greenhouse gasses will probably have reached levels before the year 2100 that are sufficient to raise the temperature past this warming threshold.|bibcode = 2004Natur.428..616G}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] | url = http://www.grida.no/climate/ipcc_tar/wg1/432.htm#fig1116 | title = Regional Sea Level Change | format = Figure 11.16}}</ref>  [[James E. Hansen]] suggests that inadequate attention is being given to this issue.<ref>{{cite journal |author=J E Hansen |title=Scientific reticence and sea level rise |journal=Environ. Res. Lett. |volume=2 |pages=024002 |date=April\u2013June 2007 |doi=10.1088/1748-9326/2/2/024002 |issue=2|arxiv = physics/0703220 |bibcode = 2007ERL.....2b4002H }}</ref>\n\nOne study suggests it would take 3,000 years to completely melt the Greenland ice sheet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/corporate/pressoffice/adcc/BookCh4Jan2006.pdf |title=The Role of Sea-Level Rise and the Greenland Ice Sheet in Dangerous Climate Change: Implications for the Stabilisation of Climate |last=Lowe |first=Jason |author2=Jonathan M. Gregory |author3=Jeff Ridley |author4=Philippe Huybrechts |author5=Robert J. Nicholls |author6=Matthew Collins |date=January 2006 |publisher=UK Met Office |accessdate=2009-03-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327043445/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/corporate/pressoffice/adcc/BookCh4Jan2006.pdf |archivedate=March 27, 2009 }}</ref>  This figure was derived from the assumed levels of [[greenhouse gas]]es over the duration of the experiment.\n\nAs the Greenland ice sheet loses mass from [[Ice calving|calving]] of icebergs as well as by melting of ice, any such processes tend to accelerate the loss of the ice sheet.<ref>{{Cite journal| last1 = Zwally | first1 = J.| last2 = Abdalati | first2 = W. | authorlink2=Waleed Abdalati| last3 = Herring | first3 = T.| last4 = Larson | first4 = K.| last5 = Saba | first5 = J.| last6 = Steffen | first6 = K.| title = Surface melt-induced acceleration of Greenland ice-sheet flow| journal = [[Science (journal)|Science]]| volume = 297| issue = 5579| pages = 218\u2013222| date=Jul 2002 | issn = 0036-8075| pmid = 12052902| doi = 10.1126/science.1072708|bibcode = 2002Sci...297..218Z }}</ref>\n\n==Millennial-timescale events==\nSome long-term effects happen over thousands, not hundreds, of years.\n\n===Disruption to thermohaline circulation===\n\n[[File:Thermohaline Circulation 2.png|A schematic of the path of the thermohaline circulation. Blue paths represent deep-water currents, while red paths represent surface currents|thumb|right]]\n{{See also|Shutdown of thermohaline circulation}}\n\nEarly work with simplified models suggested that global warming could cause a shutdown of the [[thermohaline circulation]].<ref>{{Cite journal| first1 = A. | title = The Stability of the Thermohaline Circulation in Global Warming Experiments | journal = Journal of Climate | volume = 12| issue =    4| last1 = Schmittner | pages = 1117\u20131133 | year = 1999| issn = 1520-0442 | doi = 10.1175/1520-0442(1999)012<1117:TSOTTC>2.0.CO;2| last2 =    Stocker | first2 =    T. F.|bibcode = 1999JCli...12.1117S }}</ref> This effect is not replicated in more sophisticated coupled ocean-atmosphere [[global climate models]], which do not shutdown but do display varying degrees of slowdown.\n\nThis may take a considerable time to occur, as Knutti and Stocker found, again from a simplified model, when :\"\u2026thermohaline shutdowns can occur thousands of years after the warming has stopped.\"<ref>{{Cite journal| first1 = R. | title = Limited Predictability of the Future Thermohaline Circulation Close to an Instability Threshold | journal = Journal of Climate | volume = 15| last1 = Knutti| issue = 2 | pages = 179\u2013186 | year = 2002| issn = 1520-0442 | doi = 10.1175/1520-0442(2002)015<0179:LPOTFT>2.0.CO;2| last2 =    Stocker | first2 =    T. F.|bibcode = 2002JCli...15..179K | citeseerx = 10.1.1.318.7273 }}</ref>\n\n===Ocean anoxia===\n{{Main|Ocean anoxia}}\n{{further|Effects of global warming on oceans}}\nOne study suggests that the amount of oxygen dissolved in the oceans may decline, with adverse consequences for ocean life.<ref>{{cite journal | pages = 105\u2013109 | volume = 2 | issue = 2| year = 2009 | doi = 10.1038/ngeo420 | journal = Nature Geoscience| last1 = Shaffer| last3 = Pedersen| last2 = Olsen | first2 = S. M.| first3 = J. O. P. | title = Long-term ocean oxygen depletion in response to carbon dioxide emissions from fossil fuels| first1 = G. .|bibcode = 2009NatGe...2..105S }}</ref> This effect was determined using a [[global climate model|model run]] of 100,000 years. The researchers predicted:\n<blockquote>\n\u2026severe, long-term ocean oxygen depletion, as well as a great expansion of ocean oxygen-minimum zones for scenarios with high emissions or high climate sensitivity. We find that climate feedbacks within the Earth system amplify the strength and duration of global warming, ocean heating and oxygen depletion. Decreased oxygen solubility from surface-layer warming accounts for most of the enhanced oxygen depletion in the upper 500 m of the ocean. Possible weakening of ocean overturning and convection lead to further oxygen depletion, also in the deep ocean.\n</blockquote>\n\nOther research by the Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences predicts that minimum oxygen zones, particularly in the pacific are expanding, with an estimated total reduction of ocean oxygen levels from 1% to 7% by the end of the century.<ref>[http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev.marine.010908.163855 Ocean Deoxygenation in a Warming World] Ralph F. Keeling, Arne K\u00f6rtzinger, and Nicolas Gruber</ref>\n\n===Clathrate decomposition===\n[[File:Gas hydrates 1996.svg|right|thumbnail|250px|Worldwide distribution of confirmed or inferred offshore gas hydrate-bearing sediments, 1996.<br />Source: [[USGS]]]]\n{{See also|Methane clathrate}}\n[[Methane clathrate]], also called methane hydrate, is a form of [[water (molecule)|water]] [[ice]] that contains a large amount of [[methane]] within its [[crystal]] structure. Extremely large deposits of methane clathrate have been found under sediments on the ocean floors of Earth (estimated at 3,000<ref>{{Cite journal| first1=B.| first2=D.| last2 = Archer| title = Global inventory of methane clathrate: sensitivity to changes in the deep ocean| url = http://geosci.uchicago.edu/~archer/reprints/buffett.2004.clathrates.pdf| journal = Earth and Planetary Science Letters| volume = 227| issue=3\u20134| pages = 185| year = 2004| last1 = Buffett| doi = 10.1016/j.epsl.2004.09.005| bibcode=2004E&PSL.227..185B}}</ref>\u201311,000<ref name=\"cite doi|10.1007/BF00144504\">{{Cite journal| pages = 247\u2013281| year = 1990| doi = 10.1007/BF00144504| first1 = G. J.| volume = 16| title = Role of methane clathrates in past and future climates| journal = Climatic Change| last1 = Macdonald| issue = 3| bibcode = 1990ClCh...16..247M}}</ref> gigatonnes of carbon).\n\nMacDonald suggests clathrate volumes are \"about 11,000 Gt of carbon for ocean sediments, and about 400 Gt for sediments under permafrost regions\".<ref name=\"cite doi|10.1007/BF00144504\"/>  Buffett and Archer predict \"eventual releases of 2000\u20134000 Gt C in response to a ~2000 Gt C anthropogenic carbon release\",<ref>{{Cite journal| first1=D.| last2=Buffett| first2=B.| url=http://geosci.uchicago.edu/~archer/reprints/archer.2005.clathrates.pdf| last1= Archer| title = Time-dependent response of the global ocean clathrate reservoir to climatic and anthropogenic forcing| journal = Geochemistry Geophysics Geosystems| volume = 6| issue=3| pages = Q03002| year = 2005| doi = 10.1029/2004GC000854|bibcode = 2005GGG.....603002A }}</ref> for which they suggest no timescale.\n\nArcher considered the timescale and determined that \"\u2026on longer time scales of 1\u201310 [thousand years], there may be a positive feedback with ocean temperature, amplifying the long-term climate impact of anthropogenic {{chem|CO|2}} release.\"<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/j.epsl.2004.03.011| year = 2004| pages = 333\u2013348| last2 =  Martin| last3 =  Buffett| last6 =  Ganopolski| last5 =  Rahmstorf| last4 =  Brovkin| first1 = D.| volume = 222| first3 = B. | first2 = P.| last1 = Archer| journal = Earth and Planetary Science Letters| first4 = V.| title = The importance of ocean temperature to global biogeochemistry| first6 = A.| first5 = S.| issue = 2| bibcode=2004E&PSL.222..333A}}</ref>\n\n=== Carbon dioxide levels in the atmosphere ===\n\nStabilizing the global average temperature would require large reductions in [[Carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]] emissions,<ref name=\"long-term effects of global warming\">\n* Summary, [http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=12877&page=14 pp. 14\u201319], in {{harvnb|National Research Council|2011}}\n* FAQ 12.3, in: [http://www.climatechange2013.org/images/uploads/WGIAR5_WGI-12Doc2b_FinalDraft_Chapter12.pdf Chapter 12: Long-term Climate Change: Projections, Commitments and Irreversibility], in {{harvnb|IPCC AR5 WG1|2013}}, pp. 88\u201389 (pp. 90\u201391 of PDF chapter)\n</ref> as well as reductions in emissions of other greenhouse gases such as methane and nitrous oxide.<ref name=\"long-term effects of global warming\"/><ref>[http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=12877&page=65 BOX 2.1: Stabilization and Non-CO<sub>2</sub> Greenhouse Gases (p. 65)], in: [http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=12877&page=59 Chapter 2: Emissions, Concentrations, and Related Factors], in {{harvnb|National Research Council|2011}}\n</ref> Emissions of CO<sub>2</sub> would need to be reduced by more than 80% relative to their peak level.<ref name=\"long-term effects of global warming\"/> Even if this were achieved, global average temperatures would remain close to their highest level for many centuries, prolonging the current [[interglacial]] period by at least 100,000 years.<ref>{{cite journal\n | last =Crucifix\n | first =Michel\n | title =Earth's narrow escape from a big freeze\n | journal =Nature\n | volume =529\n | issue =7585\n | pages =162\u2013163\n | date =14 January 2016\n | issn =1476-4687\n | doi =10.1038/529162a\n | pmid =26762453\n | doi-access =free\n }}</ref><ref name=\"long-term effects of global warming\"/>  As of 2016, emissions of CO<sub>2</sub> from burning fossil fuels had stopped increasing, but [[The Guardian]] reports they need to be \"reduced to have a real impact on climate change\".  Meanwhile, this greenhouse gas continues to accumulate in the atmosphere.<ref>{{cite news|title=The world's carbon-dioxide emissions have stabilised|url=https://www.economist.com/news/business-and-finance/21694972-they-need-fall-have-real-impact-climate-change-worlds-carbon|accessdate=12 December 2016|work=The Economist|date=16 March 2016}}</ref> In that context, the [[The New York Times|New York Times]] reported that scientific installations analyzing oceanic air detected the excess carbon dioxide in the atmosphere \"rose at the highest rate on record in 2015 and 2016.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/26/climate/carbon-in-atmosphere-is-rising-even-as-emissions-stabilize.html|title=Carbon in Atmosphere Is Rising, Even as Emissions Stabilize|last=Gillis|first=Justin|date=2017-06-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-06-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It has been suggested that this rise in CO<sub>2</sub> levels is the result of changing absorption patterns of the ocean and land surface in that they may have reached the limit of their ability to absorb carbon dioxide.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Long-term return to equilibrium==\n{{further|Oceanic carbon cycle}}\nAfter the [[Paleocene\u2013Eocene Thermal Maximum|PETM]] peak there was an extended period of cooling or \"climate whiplash\".<ref name=NYT112815>{{cite news|author1=Curt Stager|title=Tales of a Warmer Planet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/29/opinion/sunday/tales-of-a-warmer-planet.html|accessdate=November 30, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=November 28, 2015|quote=From the perspective of future generations, the whiplash and subsequent cooling that follows our own thermal peak could be as challenging as the warming.}}</ref>\n\nWhile the warm surface waters of the oceans have limited ability to absorb anthropogenic carbon dioxide, the coldest surface waters near the poles (2\u20133% of ocean surfaces) can transfer significant amounts of carbon dioxide to deep-ocean reserves. Over a period of many centuries, this process and the process of calcium carbonate absorption of carbon dioxide on land and in the oceans will remove 60\u201380% of the excess carbon dioxide.<ref name=longthaw>{{Cite book |title=The Long Thaw: How Humans Are Changing the Next 100,000 Years of Earth's Climate |author=David Archer |year=2009 |page=109 |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |isbn=978-0-691-13654-7}}</ref>\n\n[[Igneous rock]] when exposed to a near surface environment absorbs carbon dioxide through a very slow [[weathering]] rate, but weathering increases in a warmer, higher rainfall climate, speeding the process. This geological weathering will absorb the remaining 20\u201340% of anthropogenic carbon dioxide over the period of tens of thousands to hundreds of thousands of years.<ref name=longthaw />\n\nAnother way to bring these long term effects back to equilibrium is to understand to nature of coupled natural and human systems. If more research is done on the feedbacks of these systems, there can be better approaches on how to mitigate the negative effects that are derived from these systems. [[Environmental factor#Socioeconomic Drivers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Global warming|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Long-Term Effects Of Global Warming}}\n[[Category:Effects of global warming|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:Sea level rise projections for the 21st century.png|thumb|Sea level rise projections for the 21st century.]]\n:''See also [[Effects of global warming]]. The focus of this article is on the effects beyond 2100.''\n\nThere are expected to be various '''long-term effects of global warming'''. Most discussion and research, including that by the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] (IPCC) reports, concentrates on the effects of [[global warming]] up to 2100, with only an outline of the effects beyond this.\n\n==Ice loss and sea level rise==\n[[File:Larsen B collapse.jpg|thumb|The collapse of [[Larsen Ice Shelf|Larsen B Shelf]], showing the diminishing extent of the shelf from 1998 to 2002]]\n{{Main|Arctic shrinkage}}\n\n[[Meltwater]] from melting [[ice sheet]]s and [[Retreat of glaciers since 1850|glacier retreat]] contributes to a rise in the [[future sea level]].<ref name=\"TAR 11.3\" />\n\n===Antarctica===\nConcern has been expressed about the stability of the [[West Antarctic ice sheet]] (WAIS). In 2002 [[David Vaughan (scientist)|Vaughan]] & Spouge argued that the \"WAIS most likely will not collapse in the next few centuries.\"<ref>{{Cite journal| first1 = D. G.| first2 = J. R. | journal = Climatic Change | volume = 52| last1 = Vaughan | pages = 65\u201300 | year = 2002 | doi = 10.1023/A:1013038920600|title=Risk Estimation of Collapse of the West Antarctic Ice Sheet| last2 =    Spouge}}</ref>  In an inaugural article for members of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]] elected in 2005, [[Timothy Lenton]] and others suggest that a collapse of the West Antarctic ice sheet could occur within a millennium. Specifically, they state \"Although the timescale is highly uncertain, a qualitative WAIS change could occur within this millennium, with collapse within 300 years being a worst-case scenario. Rapid sea-level rise (greater than 1 m per century) is more likely to come from the WAIS than from the [[Greenland ice sheet]].\".<ref name=lenton>{{Cite journal | last1 = Lenton | first1 = T. M. | last2 = Held | first2 = H. | last3 = Kriegler | first3 = E. | last4 = Hall | first4 = J. W. | last5 = Lucht | first5 = W. | last6 = Rahmstorf | first6 = S. | last7 = Schellnhuber | first7 = H. J. | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0705414105 | title = Inaugural Article: Tipping elements in the Earth's climate system | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume = 105 | issue = 6 | pages = 1786\u20131793 | year = 2008 | pmid =  18258748| pmc = 2538841| bibcode=2008PNAS..105.1786L}}</ref> A study in 2015 found that assuming cumulative fossil fuel emissions of 10&nbsp;000 gigatonnes of carbon, the Antarctic Ice Sheet could melt completely over the following millennia, contributing 58 m to global sea-level rise, and 30 m within the first 1000 years.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Winkelmann | first1 = Ricarda | last2 = Levermann | first2 = Anders | last3 = Ridgwell | first3 = Andy | last4 = Caldeira | first4 = Ken | year = 2015 | title = Combustion of available fossil fuel resources sufficient to eliminate the Antarctic Ice Sheet | url = | journal = Science Advances | volume = 1 | issue = 8| page = e1500589 | doi = 10.1126/sciadv.1500589 | pmid = 26601273 | pmc = 4643791 | bibcode = 2015SciA....1E0589W }}</ref>\n\n===Greenland===\n[[Greenland ice sheet|Greenland's ice sheet]] contains enough [[fresh water]] as ice to raise sea level worldwide by {{convert|7|m|ft|0}}.<ref name=\"TAR 11.3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.grida.no/climate/ipcc_tar/wg1/412.htm#tab113 |title=Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis |publisher=[[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] |format=Table 11.3 |date=2001-02-16 |accessdate=2007-12-24}}</ref>  Greenland may become warm enough by 2100 to begin an almost complete melt over more than 1,000 years.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Gregory JM |authorlink=Jonathan M. Gregory |author2=Huybrechts P |author3=Raper SC |title=Climatology: threatened loss of the Greenland ice-sheet |journal=Nature |volume=428 |issue=6983 |pages=616 |date=April 2004 |pmid=15071587 |doi=10.1038/428616a |url=http://homepages.vub.ac.be/~phuybrec/pdf/Nature.Green.2004.pdf |quote=The Greenland ice-sheet would melt faster in a warmer climate and is likely to be eliminated \u2014 except for residual glaciers in the mountains \u2014 if the annual average temperature in Greenland increases by more than about 3 \u00b0C. This would raise the global average sea-level by 7 metres over a period of 1000 years or more. We show here that concentrations of greenhouse gasses will probably have reached levels before the year 2100 that are sufficient to raise the temperature past this warming threshold.|bibcode = 2004Natur.428..616G}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] | url = http://www.grida.no/climate/ipcc_tar/wg1/432.htm#fig1116 | title = Regional Sea Level Change | format = Figure 11.16}}</ref>  [[James E. Hansen]] suggests that inadequate attention is being given to this issue.<ref>{{cite journal |author=J E Hansen |title=Scientific reticence and sea level rise |journal=Environ. Res. Lett. |volume=2 |pages=024002 |date=April\u2013June 2007 |doi=10.1088/1748-9326/2/2/024002 |issue=2|arxiv = physics/0703220 |bibcode = 2007ERL.....2b4002H }}</ref>\n\nOne study suggests it would take 3,000 years to completely melt the Greenland ice sheet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/corporate/pressoffice/adcc/BookCh4Jan2006.pdf |title=The Role of Sea-Level Rise and the Greenland Ice Sheet in Dangerous Climate Change: Implications for the Stabilisation of Climate |last=Lowe |first=Jason |author2=Jonathan M. Gregory |author3=Jeff Ridley |author4=Philippe Huybrechts |author5=Robert J. Nicholls |author6=Matthew Collins |date=January 2006 |publisher=UK Met Office |accessdate=2009-03-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327043445/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/corporate/pressoffice/adcc/BookCh4Jan2006.pdf |archivedate=March 27, 2009 }}</ref>  This figure was derived from the assumed levels of [[greenhouse gas]]es over the duration of the experiment.\n\nAs the Greenland ice sheet loses mass from [[Ice calving|calving]] of icebergs as well as by melting of ice, any such processes tend to accelerate the loss of the ice sheet.<ref>{{Cite journal| last1 = Zwally | first1 = J.| last2 = Abdalati | first2 = W. | authorlink2=Waleed Abdalati| last3 = Herring | first3 = T.| last4 = Larson | first4 = K.| last5 = Saba | first5 = J.| last6 = Steffen | first6 = K.| title = Surface melt-induced acceleration of Greenland ice-sheet flow| journal = [[Science (journal)|Science]]| volume = 297| issue = 5579| pages = 218\u2013222| date=Jul 2002 | issn = 0036-8075| pmid = 12052902| doi = 10.1126/science.1072708|bibcode = 2002Sci...297..218Z }}</ref>\n\n==Millennial-timescale events==\nSome long-term effects happen over thousands, not hundreds, of years.\n\n===Disruption to thermohaline circulation===\n\n[[File:Thermohaline Circulation 2.png|A schematic of the path of the thermohaline circulation. Blue paths represent deep-water currents, while red paths represent surface currents|thumb|right]]\n{{See also|Shutdown of thermohaline circulation}}\n\nEarly work with simplified models suggested that global warming could cause a shutdown of the [[thermohaline circulation]].<ref>{{Cite journal| first1 = A. | title = The Stability of the Thermohaline Circulation in Global Warming Experiments | journal = Journal of Climate | volume = 12| issue =    4| last1 = Schmittner | pages = 1117\u20131133 | year = 1999| issn = 1520-0442 | doi = 10.1175/1520-0442(1999)012<1117:TSOTTC>2.0.CO;2| last2 =    Stocker | first2 =    T. F.|bibcode = 1999JCli...12.1117S }}</ref> This effect is not replicated in more sophisticated coupled ocean-atmosphere [[global climate models]], which do not shutdown but do display varying degrees of slowdown.\n\nThis may take a considerable time to occur, as Knutti and Stocker found, again from a simplified model, when :\"\u2026thermohaline shutdowns can occur thousands of years after the warming has stopped.\"<ref>{{Cite journal| first1 = R. | title = Limited Predictability of the Future Thermohaline Circulation Close to an Instability Threshold | journal = Journal of Climate | volume = 15| last1 = Knutti| issue = 2 | pages = 179\u2013186 | year = 2002| issn = 1520-0442 | doi = 10.1175/1520-0442(2002)015<0179:LPOTFT>2.0.CO;2| last2 =    Stocker | first2 =    T. F.|bibcode = 2002JCli...15..179K | citeseerx = 10.1.1.318.7273 }}</ref>\n\n===Ocean anoxia===\n{{Main|Ocean anoxia}}\n{{further|Effects of global warming on oceans}}\nOne study suggests that the amount of oxygen dissolved in the oceans may decline, with adverse consequences for ocean life.<ref>{{cite journal | pages = 105\u2013109 | volume = 2 | issue = 2| year = 2009 | doi = 10.1038/ngeo420 | journal = Nature Geoscience| last1 = Shaffer| last3 = Pedersen| last2 = Olsen | first2 = S. M.| first3 = J. O. P. | title = Long-term ocean oxygen depletion in response to carbon dioxide emissions from fossil fuels| first1 = G. .|bibcode = 2009NatGe...2..105S }}</ref> This effect was determined using a [[global climate model|model run]] of 100,000 years. The researchers predicted:\n<blockquote>\n\u2026severe, long-term ocean oxygen depletion, as well as a great expansion of ocean oxygen-minimum zones for scenarios with high emissions or high climate sensitivity. We find that climate feedbacks within the Earth system amplify the strength and duration of global warming, ocean heating and oxygen depletion. Decreased oxygen solubility from surface-layer warming accounts for most of the enhanced oxygen depletion in the upper 500 m of the ocean. Possible weakening of ocean overturning and convection lead to further oxygen depletion, also in the deep ocean.\n</blockquote>\n\nOther research by the Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences predicts that minimum oxygen zones, particularly in the pacific are expanding, with an estimated total reduction of ocean oxygen levels from 1% to 7% by the end of the century.<ref>[http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev.marine.010908.163855 Ocean Deoxygenation in a Warming World] Ralph F. Keeling, Arne K\u00f6rtzinger, and Nicolas Gruber</ref>\n\n===Clathrate decomposition===\n[[File:Gas hydrates 1996.svg|right|thumbnail|250px|Worldwide distribution of confirmed or inferred offshore gas hydrate-bearing sediments, 1996.<br />Source: [[USGS]]]]\n{{See also|Methane clathrate}}\n[[Methane clathrate]], also called methane hydrate, is a form of [[water (molecule)|water]] [[ice]] that contains a large amount of [[methane]] within its [[crystal]] structure. Extremely large deposits of methane clathrate have been found under sediments on the ocean floors of Earth (estimated at 3,000<ref>{{Cite journal| first1=B.| first2=D.| last2 = Archer| title = Global inventory of methane clathrate: sensitivity to changes in the deep ocean| url = http://geosci.uchicago.edu/~archer/reprints/buffett.2004.clathrates.pdf| journal = Earth and Planetary Science Letters| volume = 227| issue=3\u20134| pages = 185| year = 2004| last1 = Buffett| doi = 10.1016/j.epsl.2004.09.005| bibcode=2004E&PSL.227..185B}}</ref>\u201311,000<ref name=\"cite doi|10.1007/BF00144504\">{{Cite journal| pages = 247\u2013281| year = 1990| doi = 10.1007/BF00144504| first1 = G. J.| volume = 16| title = Role of methane clathrates in past and future climates| journal = Climatic Change| last1 = Macdonald| issue = 3| bibcode = 1990ClCh...16..247M}}</ref> gigatonnes of carbon).\n\nMacDonald suggests clathrate volumes are \"about 11,000 Gt of carbon for ocean sediments, and about 400 Gt for sediments under permafrost regions\".<ref name=\"cite doi|10.1007/BF00144504\"/>  Buffett and Archer predict \"eventual releases of 2000\u20134000 Gt C in response to a ~2000 Gt C anthropogenic carbon release\",<ref>{{Cite journal| first1=D.| last2=Buffett| first2=B.| url=http://geosci.uchicago.edu/~archer/reprints/archer.2005.clathrates.pdf| last1= Archer| title = Time-dependent response of the global ocean clathrate reservoir to climatic and anthropogenic forcing| journal = Geochemistry Geophysics Geosystems| volume = 6| issue=3| pages = Q03002| year = 2005| doi = 10.1029/2004GC000854|bibcode = 2005GGG.....603002A }}</ref> for which they suggest no timescale.\n\nArcher considered the timescale and determined that \"\u2026on longer time scales of 1\u201310 [thousand years], there may be a positive feedback with ocean temperature, amplifying the long-term climate impact of anthropogenic {{chem|CO|2}} release.\"<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/j.epsl.2004.03.011| year = 2004| pages = 333\u2013348| last2 =  Martin| last3 =  Buffett| last6 =  Ganopolski| last5 =  Rahmstorf| last4 =  Brovkin| first1 = D.| volume = 222| first3 = B. | first2 = P.| last1 = Archer| journal = Earth and Planetary Science Letters| first4 = V.| title = The importance of ocean temperature to global biogeochemistry| first6 = A.| first5 = S.| issue = 2| bibcode=2004E&PSL.222..333A}}</ref>\n\n=== Carbon dioxide levels in the atmosphere ===\n\nStabilizing the global average temperature would require large reductions in [[Carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]] emissions,<ref name=\"long-term effects of global warming\">\n* Summary, [http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=12877&page=14 pp. 14\u201319], in {{harvnb|National Research Council|2011}}\n* FAQ 12.3, in: [http://www.climatechange2013.org/images/uploads/WGIAR5_WGI-12Doc2b_FinalDraft_Chapter12.pdf Chapter 12: Long-term Climate Change: Projections, Commitments and Irreversibility], in {{harvnb|IPCC AR5 WG1|2013}}, pp. 88\u201389 (pp. 90\u201391 of PDF chapter)\n</ref> as well as reductions in emissions of other greenhouse gases such as methane and nitrous oxide.<ref name=\"long-term effects of global warming\"/><ref>[http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=12877&page=65 BOX 2.1: Stabilization and Non-CO<sub>2</sub> Greenhouse Gases (p. 65)], in: [http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=12877&page=59 Chapter 2: Emissions, Concentrations, and Related Factors], in {{harvnb|National Research Council|2011}}\n</ref> Emissions of CO<sub>2</sub> would need to be reduced by more than 80% relative to their peak level.<ref name=\"long-term effects of global warming\"/> Even if this were achieved, global average temperatures would remain close to their highest level for many centuries, prolonging the current [[interglacial]] period by at least 100,000 years.<ref>{{cite journal\n | last =Crucifix\n | first =Michel\n | title =Earth's narrow escape from a big freeze\n | journal =Nature\n | volume =529\n | issue =7585\n | pages =162\u2013163\n | date =14 January 2016\n | issn =1476-4687\n | doi =10.1038/529162a\n | pmid =26762453\n | doi-access =free\n }}</ref><ref name=\"long-term effects of global warming\"/>  As of 2016, emissions of CO<sub>2</sub> from burning fossil fuels had stopped increasing, but [[The Guardian]] reports they need to be \"reduced to have a real impact on climate change\".  Meanwhile, this greenhouse gas continues to accumulate in the atmosphere.<ref>{{cite news|title=The world's carbon-dioxide emissions have stabilised|url=https://www.economist.com/news/business-and-finance/21694972-they-need-fall-have-real-impact-climate-change-worlds-carbon|accessdate=12 December 2016|work=The Economist|date=16 March 2016}}</ref> In that context, the [[The New York Times|New York Times]] reported that scientific installations analyzing oceanic air detected the excess carbon dioxide in the atmosphere \"rose at the highest rate on record in 2015 and 2016.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/26/climate/carbon-in-atmosphere-is-rising-even-as-emissions-stabilize.html|title=Carbon in Atmosphere Is Rising, Even as Emissions Stabilize|last=Gillis|first=Justin|date=2017-06-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-06-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It has been suggested that this rise in CO<sub>2</sub> levels is the result of changing absorption patterns of the ocean and land surface in that they may have reached the limit of their ability to absorb carbon dioxide.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Long-term return to equilibrium==\n{{further|Oceanic carbon cycle}}\nAfter the [[Paleocene\u2013Eocene Thermal Maximum|PETM]] peak there was an extended period of cooling or \"climate whiplash\".<ref name=NYT112815>{{cite news|author1=Curt Stager|title=Tales of a Warmer Planet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/29/opinion/sunday/tales-of-a-warmer-planet.html|accessdate=November 30, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=November 28, 2015|quote=From the perspective of future generations, the whiplash and subsequent cooling that follows our own thermal peak could be as challenging as the warming.}}</ref>\n\nWhile the warm surface waters of the oceans have limited ability to absorb anthropogenic carbon dioxide, the coldest surface waters near the poles (2\u20133% of ocean surfaces) can transfer significant amounts of carbon dioxide to deep-ocean reserves. Over a period of many centuries, this process and the process of calcium carbonate absorption of carbon dioxide on land and in the oceans will remove 60\u201380% of the excess carbon dioxide.<ref name=longthaw>{{Cite book |title=The Long Thaw: How Humans Are Changing the Next 100,000 Years of Earth's Climate |author=David Archer |year=2009 |page=109 |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |isbn=978-0-691-13654-7}}</ref>\n\n[[Igneous rock]] when exposed to a near surface environment absorbs carbon dioxide through a very slow [[weathering]] rate, but weathering increases in a warmer, higher rainfall climate, speeding the process. This geological weathering will absorb the remaining 20\u201340% of anthropogenic carbon dioxide over the period of tens of thousands to hundreds of thousands of years.<ref name=longthaw />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Global warming|state=expanded}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Long-Term Effects Of Global Warming}}\n[[Category:Effects of global warming|*]]\n", "name_user": "Lfabina", "label": "safe", "comment": "added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long-term_effects_of_global_warming"}
{"title_page": "Naledi Pandor", "text_new": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use South African English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|name             = Naledi Pandor\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n|image            = Minister N Pandor - TWAS (2010) (cropped).jpg\n|caption          = Pandor in 2010\n<!-- -->\n|office           = [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]\n|deputy           = [[Alvin Botes]]<br />[[Candith Mashego-Dlamini]]\n|term_start       = 30 May 2019\n|term_end         = \n|president        = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor      = [[Lindiwe Sisulu]]\n<!-- -->\n|office1          = [[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]]\n| deputy1         = [[Buti Manamela]]\n|term_start1      = 27 February 2018\n|term_end1        = 29 May 2019\n|president1       = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor1     = [[Hlengiwe Mkhize]]\n|successor1       = ''Ministry split''\n<!-- -->\n|office2          = [[Department of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]\n|deputy2          = [[Zanele kaMagwaza-Msibi]]\n|president2       = [[Jacob Zuma]]<br />[[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|term_start2      = 26 May 2014\n|term_end2        = 26 February 2018\n|predecessor2     = [[Derek Hanekom]]\n|successor2       = [[Nkhensani Kubayi-Ngubane]]\n|president3       = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|deputy3          = [[Zanele kaMagwaza-Msibi]]\n|term_start3      = 10 May 2009\n|term_end3        = 4 October 2012\n|predecessor3     = [[Mosibudi Mangena]]\n|successor3       = [[Derek Hanekom]]\n<!-- -->\n|office4          = [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]]\n|deputy4          = [[Fatima Chohan]]\n|president4       = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|term_start4      = 4 October 2012\n|term_end4        = 25 May 2014<br /><small>[[Acting (law)|Acting]]: 2 \u2013 4 October 2012</small>\n|predecessor4     = [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]]\n|successor4       = [[Malusi Gigaba]]\n<!-- -->\n|office5          = [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]\n|deputy5          = [[Enver Surty]]\n|president5       = [[Thabo Mbeki]]<br />[[Kgalema Motlanthe]]\n|term_start5      = 12 May 2004\n|term_end5        = 10 May 2009\n|predecessor5     = [[Kader Asmal]]\n|successor5       = ''Ministry split''\n<!-- -->\n|office6          = [[President of the Senate of South Africa|Chairperson of the National Council of Provinces]]\n|president6       = [[Thabo Mbeki]]\n|term_start6      = 21 June 1999\n|term_end6        = 4 May 2004\n|predecessor6     = [[Mosiuoa Lekota]]\n|successor6       = [[Joyce Kgoali]]\n<!-- -->\n|birth_name       = Grace Naledi Mandisa Matthews\n|birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1953|12|7}}\n|birth_place      = [[Durban]], [[Natal Province]], [[Union of South Africa]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|alma_mater       = {{Flatlist|\n* [[University of Botswana]]\n* [[University of Swaziland]]\n* [[University of London]]\n* [[Kennedy School of Government]]\n* [[Stellenbosch University]]\n* [[University of Pretoria]]\n}}\n|party            = [[African National Congress]]\n|relations        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Z. K. Matthews]] (grandfather)\n* [[Joe Matthews (politician)|Joe Matthews]] (father)\n}}\n|spouse           = Sharif Joseph Pandor\n|children         = 4\n|residence        = \n|occupation       = \n|signature        = \n|website          = \n|footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor''' (n\u00e9e '''Matthews'''; born 7 December 1953) is a South African academic, educationist, lecturer and politician serving as the [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]] since 2019. She has served as a [[Parliament of South Africa|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) since 1994.\n\nBorn in [[Durban]], Pandor completed high school in [[Botswana]]. She qualified as a teacher and taught at multiple schools and universities, whilst she achieved various degrees from different universities.<ref name=\"Ministers\">{{cite news |title=Ministers |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2005-12-01-ministers |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=1 December 2005 |archiveurl=https://mg.co.za/article/2005-12-01-ministers |archivedate=10 November 2019}}</ref> Pandor took office as a Member of Parliament in 1994.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She soon became Deputy Chief Whip of the ANC caucus in 1995.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She was elected Deputy Chairperson of the [[National Council of Provinces]] in 1998 and became Chairperson in 1999.<ref name=\"Ministers\" />\n\nShe initially became a member of the national cabinet in 2004, following President [[Thabo Mbeki]]'s decision to appoint her as [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Meet Mbeki's 'delivery' team |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/meet-mbekis-delivery-team-211708 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=29 April 2004}}</ref> She retained her post in the cabinet of [[Kgalema Motlanthe]]. Newly-elected President [[Jacob Zuma]] named her [[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jacob Zuma announces cabinet choices |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/jacob-zuma-announces-cabinet-choices |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=10 May 2009}}</ref> She served in the position until her appointment as [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cabinet reshuffle on cards |url=https://www.iol.co.za/the-star/soweto/cabinet-reshuffle-on-cards-1396039 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=4 October 2012}}</ref> She returned to the post of Minister of Science and Technology in 2014 and held it until 2018, when she became [[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]] in the [[First Cabinet of Cyril Ramaphosa|first cabinet of President Cyril Ramaphosa]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicolson |first1=Greg |title=Who\u2019s Who of the Zuma\u2019s new Cabinet |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2014-05-26-whos-who-of-the-zumas-new-cabinet/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunter |first1=Qaanitah |title=Ramaphosa swings the axe, cuts 13 from Zuma's Cabinet |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-02-26-ramaphosa-swings-the-axe-cuts-14-from-zumas-cabinet/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2019 general elections, Pandor was mentioned as a possible candidate for [[Deputy President of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Calls mount for SA to appoint female deputy president |url=https://www.enca.com/news/sa-speculates-who-could-be-second |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=23 May 2019}}</ref> She was instead appointed Minister of International Relations and Cooperation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Du Plessis |first1=Carien |title=Diplomats hail Naledi Pandor\u2019s new International Relations job |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-05-31-diplomats-hail-naledi-pandors-new-international-relations-job/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nGrace Naledi Mandisa Matthews was born on 7 December 1953 in [[Durban]], [[Natal Province|Natal]] to Regina Thelma (died 2002) and [[Joe Matthews (politician)|Joe Matthews]] (1929\u20132010), a political and anti-apartheid activist and the son of black academic [[Z. K. Matthews]] (1901\u20131968).<ref>{{cite news |title=Former deputy minister Joe Matthews dies |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2010-08-19-former-deputy-minister-joe-matthews-dies |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=19 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Minister Naledi Pandor\u2019s father, Joe Matthews, dies |url=https://www.gov.za/minister-naledi-pandor%E2%80%99s-father-joe-matthews-dies |website=South African Government |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref> She received her primary and secondary education in [[Botswana]]. She matriculated from Gaborone Secondary School. Between 1973 and 1977, she achieved a Certificate for Continuing Education and bachelor's degree from the [[University of Swaziland]] and the [[University of Botswana]], respectively.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She proceeded to head overseas and fulfilled a Diploma in Education and an MA degree from the [[University of London]] between 1978 and 1979.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /><ref name=\"timeslive1604\">{{cite news |title=Higher education's Naledi Pandor caps string of qualifications with doctorate |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-04-16-higher-educations-naledi-pandor-caps-string-of-qualifications-with-doctorate/ |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nPandir obtained a Diploma in Higher Education, Administration and Leadership from Bryn Mawr Summer Programme in 1992, and soon enrolled at the [[Kennedy School of Government]] to receive a Diploma in Leadership in Development in 1997. She also attained an MA degree in Linguistics from the [[University of Stellenbosch]] in the same year.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> Pandor received her PhD in Education at the [[University of Pretoria]] in 2019, with a thesis titled \"The contested meaning of transformation in higher education in post-apartheid South Africa\".<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Petersen |first1=Tammy |title=Minister Pandor walks the walk, graduating with PhD in Education |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/minister-pandor-walks-the-walk-graduating-with-phd-in-education-20190416 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=LOOK: 'She continues to inspire us': Naledi Pandor awarded PhD |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/look-she-continues-to-inspire-us-naledi-pandor-awarded-phd-21444274 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=16 April 2019 |location=Pretoria, Gauteng}}</ref>\n\n==Teaching career==\nPandor became a teacher at the Ernest Bevin School in [[London]] in 1980. She was soon employed as a teacher in [[Gaborone]] in 1981 and worked as one until 1984. She proceeded to serve as an instructor at the Taung College of Education from 1984 to 1986. Pandor worked as a senior lecturer in English at the [[University of Bophuthatswana]] from 1986 to 1989. She soon worked as a senior fellow in the Academic Support Programme of the [[University of Cape Town]] between 1989 and 1994.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nWhile at the University of Bophuthatswana, Pandor served as the chair of the university's Union of Democratic Staff Associations between 1988 and 1990. She was appointed the chairperson of the Western Cape National Executive Committee of the National Education Coordinating Committee in 1991 and served in the position until 1993. At the same time, she was part of the ANC's Western Cape Education Committee.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nAdditionally, Pandor chaired the ANC Athlone Central branch, whilst serving as both the head of the Desmond Tutu Education Trust and the Western Cape School Building Trust.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nFrom 1992 to 1995, she worked as deputy head of the Tertiary Education Fund of South Africa. She soon became head of the fund. She was also deputy chairperson of the Joint Education Trust Board of Trustees between 1993 and 2001.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nShe was chancellor of Cape Technikon from 2002 to 2004. During the same period, she was a member of the governing council of the [[University of Fort Hare]].<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n[[File:Naledi Pandor 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Pandor at the opening exhibition of the German-South African Science Year in Cape Town in 2012]]\nPandor became a Member of the Parliament in the lower house of Parliament, the [[National Assembly of South Africa|National Assembly]], following the [[1994 South African general election|1994 general election]].<ref name=\"encaex\">{{cite news |title=EXPLAINER: Who is Naledi Pandor? |url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/who-is-naledi-pandor |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=6 November 2017}}</ref> Within the ANC caucus, she served as Deputy Chief Whip from 1995 until her deployment to the upper house of Parliament, the [[National Council of Provinces]], in 1998. She served as Deputy Chairperson until her appointment as Chairperson following the [[1999 South African general election|1999 general election]]. She succeeded inaugural Chairperson [[Mosioua Lekota]] when she assumed the office on 21 June 1999. She was the first woman to hold the role. [[Joyce Kgoali]] succeeded Pandor in 2004 and consequently became the second woman to hold the role.<ref name=\"encaex\" />\n\nPandor returned to the National Assembly following the [[2004 South African general election|2004 general election]]. President [[Thabo Mbeki]] appointed her to the role of [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]. She took office on 12 May 2004.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mbeki's cabinet list |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Mbekis-cabinet-list-20040428 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=28 April 2004}}</ref> During her tenure in the portfolio, she was responsible for a complete overhaul of the nation's education system. Pandor initiated reforms to the country's failed implementation of the [[outcomes-based education]] (OBE) system.<ref>{{cite news |title=Own-language schooling, for free |url=https://www.brandsouthafrica.com/governance/education/curriculum-180505 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Brand South Africa |date=18 May 2005}}</ref> Mbeki resigned in 2008 and left [[Kgalema Motlanthe]] in charge. Motlanthe retained Pandor in her position in his interim cabinet.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Motlanthe sworn in as interim president |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2008-09-25-motlanthe-sworn-in-as-interim-president |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=25 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=President Motlanthe\u2019s new cabinet |url=https://www.brandsouthafrica.com/governance/developmentnews/cabinet260908 |website=Brand South Africa |accessdate=24 September 2019|date=26 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Harsh Vardhan with the Vice Minister for Science, Technology and Innovation of Brazil, Mr. \u00c1lvaro Toubes Prata, the Deputy Minister of Federation of Russia, Mr. Alexey Lopatia (1).jpg|thumb|Pandor and her ministerial counterparts at the 4th BRICS Science & Technology Ministers Meeting in 2016]]\nFollowing the [[2009 South African general election|2009 general election]], Jacob Zuma became the new President of South Africa. He unbundled the Education Ministry into two new portfolios and appointed Pandor to the newly-established post of [[Minister of Science and Technology]] in May 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rossouw |first1=Mandy |title=Zuma's Cabinet: Those who didn't make the cut |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-10-zumas-cabinet-those-who-didnt-make-the-cut |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=10 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=South Africa Cabinet Members 2009 to 2010 |url=https://www.sahistory.org.za/article/south-africa-cabinet-members-2009-2010 |website=South African History Online |accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref> During her time in the position, Pandor served as a driving force for South Africa to host the [[Square Kilometre Array]] (SKA) in the Karoo region. South Africa won the bid.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tshivhidzo |first1=Edwin |title=SA will win bid to host SKA - Pandor |url=https://www.sanews.gov.za/south-africa/sa-will-win-bid-host-ska-pandor |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=SA News |date=31 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Richard |title=South Africa eyes SKA telescope with bated breath |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-02-15-south-africa-eyes-ska-telescope-with-bated-breath |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=15 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=President Zuma congratulates Minister of Science and Technology on winning the bid to host the SKA |url=https://www.gov.za/president-zuma-congratulates-minister-science-and-technology-winning-bid-host-ska |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=South African Government |date=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]] resigned as [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]] in order for her to take up the role as [[African Union|Chair of the African Union]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maasho |first1=Aaron |title=Dlamini-Zuma elected to head AU Commission |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-07-16-dlamini-zuma-elected-to-head-au-commission |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=16 July 2012}}</ref> Her resignation caused a vacancy in the cabinet. President Zuma consequently appointed Pandor as Minister of Home Affairs in an acting capacity on 2 October 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pandor appointed acting home affairs minister |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-10-02-pandor-appointed-acting-home-affairs-minister |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=2 October 2012}}</ref> Soon after on 4 October 2012, Zuma formally appointed her as Minister of Home Affairs.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Maharaj |first1=Mac |title=Naledi Pandor appointed Home Affairs minister - Presidency |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/naledi-pandor-appointed-home-affairs-minister--pre |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=3 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing her re-election in the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general election]], President Zuma announced that Pandor would return to the [[Department of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Department of Science and Technology]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Complete list of cabinet ministers |url=https://www.enca.com/elections-2014-information/president-jacob-zuma-announces-his-cabinet |accessdate=24 September 2014 |newspaper=eNCA |date=25 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Zuma shakes things up with new Cabinet |url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/zuma-shakes-things-new-cabinet |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=25 May 2014}}</ref> [[Malusi Gigaba]] succeeded her as Minister of Home Affairs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peyper |first1=Lindsey |title=Gigaba in hot seat as new Finance Minister |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/gigaba-in-hot-seat-as-new-finance-minister-20170331|newspaper=News24 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |date=31 March 2017}}</ref> She took office on 26 May 2014 and succeeded [[Derek Hanekom]].<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Quintal |first1=Genevieve |title=Marathon swearing-in for Zuma\u2019s Cabinet |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/marathon-swearing-in-for-zumas-cabinet-1694171 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Zuma names new cabinet |url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2014-05-26-zuma-names-new-cabinet/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=SowetanLIVE |date=26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Cyril Ramaphosa]] assumed the office of President in February 2018. Pandor was appointed [[Minister of Higher Education and Training]] and took office on 27 February 2018, succeeding [[Hlengiwe Mkhize]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rabkin |first1=Franny |last2=Pather |first2=Ra'eesa |title=New deputy president, finance minister announced in major Cabinet reshuffle |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-02-26-ramaphosa-cabinet-reshuffle-february-2018 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=26 February 2018 |quote=Minister of Higher education - Naledi Pandor}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Who is in and who is out: Ramaphosa's Cabinet reshuffle |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/who-is-in-and-who-is-out-ramaphosas-cabinet-reshuffle-20180226 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=26 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=IN FULL Ramaphosa hires and fires - read his Cabinet reshuffle speech |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-02-26-in-full--ramaphosa-hires-and-fires-read-his-cabinet-reshuffle-speech/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2019 South African general election|2019 general election]], the Ministry of Higher Education and Training was split. Pandor was speculated to be appointed [[Deputy President of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Dlamini-Zuma, Pandor tipped to become deputy president |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/dlamini-zuma-pandor-tipped-to-become-deputy-president-20190522 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=22 May 2019}}</ref> She was President Ramaphosa's original choice for Deputy President back in 2017 at the [[54th National Conference of the African National Congress|ANC's elective conference]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicolson |first1=Greg |title=#ANCdecides2017: The Top Six that could have been |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-12-18-ancdecides2017-the-top-six-that-could-have-been/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=18 December 2017}}</ref> She was instead appointed [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]] and assumed the post on 30 May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Introducing the executives Cyril Ramaphosa has chosen to serve SA |url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-05-30-the-men-and-women-cyril-ramaphosa-has-chosen-to-serve-sa/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=BusinessDay |date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPandor is married to Sharif Joseph Pandor, whom she met while studying in [[Botswana]], and they have four children together, Fazlur, Aisha, Suraya and Haroon. She converted to [[Islam]] after she met her husband. Her in-laws gave her the Islamic name of Nadia. On her religious conversion, Pandor said: \"My parents said God is God. As long as you worship Him we will support you and the Islamic principles are universal. Certainly, Islam demands much more of you in terms of observance.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Humble and willing to learn: Naledi Pandor is leading by example |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2019-05-19-humble-and-willing-to-learn-naledi-pandor-is-leading-by-example/ |newspaper=The Sunday Times |accessdate=23 September 2019 |date=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Naledi Pandor}}\n* {{People's Assembly (South Africa)|grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor|Naledi Pandor}}\n* [https://www.sahistory.org.za/people/grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor \u2013 South African History Online]\n* [https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor-ms Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor, Ms \u2013 South African Government]\n* [http://www.dirco.gov.za/department/profile_pandor.html  Profile: Dr Naledi Pandor, Minister \u2013 Dirco]\n* [https://www.dst.gov.za/index.php/media-room/20-temp/organogram/218-naledi-pandor-biography Naledi Pandor Biographical notes \u2013 dst.gov.za]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lindiwe Sisulu]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hlengiwe Mkhize]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Ministry split''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Derek Hanekom]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nkhensani Kubayi-Ngubane]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]]|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Malusi Gigaba]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mosibudi Mangena]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]|years=2009\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Derek Hanekom]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kader Asmal]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]|years=2004\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Ministry split''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mosiuoa Lekota]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[National Council of Provinces|Chairperson of the National Council of Provinces]]|years=1999\u20132004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Joyce Kgoali]]}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{SouthAfricaSenateNCOPPresidents}}\n{{G20-Foreign}}\n{{Thabo Mbeki cabinet 2}}\n{{Kgalema Motlanthe cabinet 1}}\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 1}}\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pandor, Naledi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Education ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Home Affairs of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Chairpersons of the National Council of Provinces]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Stellenbosch University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Eswatini alumni]]\n[[Category:South African Muslims]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam]]\n[[Category:People from Durban]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses with Star and Sash of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Female foreign ministers]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of South Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use South African English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|name             = Naledi Pandor\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n|image            = Minister N Pandor - TWAS (2010) (cropped).jpg\n|caption          = Pandor in 2010\n<!-- -->\n|office           = [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]\n|deputy           = [[Alvin Botes]]<br />[[Candith Mashego-Dlamini]]\n|term_start       = 30 May 2019\n|term_end         = \n|president        = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor      = [[Lindiwe Sisulu]]\n<!-- -->\n|office1          = [[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]]\n| deputy1         = [[Buti Manamela]]\n|term_start1      = 27 February 2018\n|term_end1        = 29 May 2019\n|president1       = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor1     = [[Hlengiwe Mkhize]]\n|successor1       = ''Ministry split''\n<!-- -->\n|office2          = [[Department of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]\n|deputy2          = [[Zanele kaMagwaza-Msibi]]\n|president2       = [[Jacob Zuma]]<br />[[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|term_start2      = 26 May 2014\n|term_end2        = 26 February 2018\n|predecessor2     = [[Derek Hanekom]]\n|successor2       = [[Nkhensani Kubayi-Ngubane]]\n|president3       = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|deputy3          = [[Zanele kaMagwaza-Msibi]]\n|term_start3      = 10 May 2009\n|term_end3        = 4 October 2012\n|predecessor3     = [[Mosibudi Mangena]]\n|successor3       = [[Derek Hanekom]]\n<!-- -->\n|office4          = [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]]\n|deputy4          = [[Fatima Chohan]]\n|president4       = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|term_start4      = 4 October 2012\n|term_end4        = 25 May 2014<br /><small>[[Acting (law)|Acting]]: 2 \u2013 4 October 2012</small>\n|predecessor4     = [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]]\n|successor4       = [[Malusi Gigaba]]\n<!-- -->\n|office5          = [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]\n|deputy5          = [[Enver Surty]]\n|president5       = [[Thabo Mbeki]]<br />[[Kgalema Motlanthe]]\n|term_start5      = 12 May 2004\n|term_end5        = 10 May 2009\n|predecessor5     = [[Kader Asmal]]\n|successor5       = ''Ministry split''\n<!-- -->\n|office6          = [[President of the Senate of South Africa|Chairperson of the National Council of Provinces]]\n|president6       = [[Thabo Mbeki]]\n|term_start6      = 21 June 1999\n|term_end6        = 4 May 2004\n|predecessor6     = [[Mosiuoa Lekota]]\n|successor6       = [[Joyce Kgoali]]\n<!-- -->\n|birth_name       = Grace Naledi Mandisa Matthews\n|birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1953|12|7}}\n|birth_place      = [[Durban]], [[Natal Province]], [[Union of South Africa]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|alma_mater       = {{Flatlist|\n* [[University of Botswana]]\n* [[University of Swaziland]]\n* [[University of London]]\n* [[Kennedy School of Government]]\n* [[Stellenbosch University]]\n* [[University of Pretoria]]\n}}\n|party            = [[African National Congress]]\n|relations        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Z. K. Matthews]] (grandfather)\n* [[Joe Matthews (politician)|Joe Matthews]] (father)\n}}\n|spouse           = Sharif Joseph Pandor\n|children         = 4\n|residence        = \n|occupation       = \n|signature        = \n|website          = \n|footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor''' (n\u00e9e '''Matthews'''; born 7 December 1953) is a South African academic, educationist, lecturer and politician serving as the [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]] since 2019. She has served as a [[Parliament of South Africa|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) since 1994.\n\nBorn in [[Durban]], Pandor completed high school in [[Botswana]]. She qualified as a teacher and taught at multiple schools and universities, whilst she achieved various degrees from different universities.<ref name=\"Ministers\">{{cite news |title=Ministers |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2005-12-01-ministers |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=1 December 2005 |archiveurl=https://mg.co.za/article/2005-12-01-ministers |archivedate=10 November 2019}}</ref> Pandor took office as a Member of Parliament in 1994.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She soon became Deputy Chief Whip of the ANC caucus in 1995.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She was elected Deputy Chairperson of the [[National Council of Provinces]] in 1998 and became Chairperson in 1999.<ref name=\"Ministers\" />\n\nShe initially became a member of the national cabinet in 2004, following President [[Thabo Mbeki]]'s decision to appoint her as [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Meet Mbeki's 'delivery' team |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/meet-mbekis-delivery-team-211708 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=29 April 2004}}</ref> She retained her post in the cabinet of [[Kgalema Motlanthe]]. Newly-elected President [[Jacob Zuma]] named her [[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jacob Zuma announces cabinet choices |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/jacob-zuma-announces-cabinet-choices |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=10 May 2009}}</ref> She served in the position until her appointment as [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cabinet reshuffle on cards |url=https://www.iol.co.za/the-star/soweto/cabinet-reshuffle-on-cards-1396039 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=4 October 2012}}</ref> She returned to the post of Minister of Science and Technology in 2014 and held it until 2018, when she became [[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]] in the [[First Cabinet of Cyril Ramaphosa|first cabinet of President Cyril Ramaphosa]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicolson |first1=Greg |title=Who\u2019s Who of the Zuma\u2019s new Cabinet |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2014-05-26-whos-who-of-the-zumas-new-cabinet/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunter |first1=Qaanitah |title=Ramaphosa swings the axe, cuts 13 from Zuma's Cabinet |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-02-26-ramaphosa-swings-the-axe-cuts-14-from-zumas-cabinet/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2019 general elections, Pandor was mentioned as a possible candidate for [[Deputy President of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Calls mount for SA to appoint female deputy president |url=https://www.enca.com/news/sa-speculates-who-could-be-second |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=23 May 2019}}</ref> She was instead appointed Minister of International Relations and Cooperation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Du Plessis |first1=Carien |title=Diplomats hail Naledi Pandor\u2019s new International Relations job |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-05-31-diplomats-hail-naledi-pandors-new-international-relations-job/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nGrace Naledi Mandisa Matthews was born on 7 December 1953 in [[Durban]], [[Natal Province|Natal]] to Regina Thelma (died 2002) and [[Joe Matthews (politician)|Joe Matthews]] (1929\u20132010), a political and anti-apartheid activist and the son of black academic [[Z. K. Matthews]] (1901\u20131968).<ref>{{cite news |title=Former deputy minister Joe Matthews dies |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2010-08-19-former-deputy-minister-joe-matthews-dies |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=19 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Minister Naledi Pandor\u2019s father, Joe Matthews, dies |url=https://www.gov.za/minister-naledi-pandor%E2%80%99s-father-joe-matthews-dies |website=South African Government |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref> She received her primary and secondary education in [[Botswana]]. She matriculated from Gaborone Secondary School. Between 1973 and 1977, she achieved a Certificate for Continuing Education and bachelor's degree from the [[University of Swaziland]] and the [[University of Botswana]], respectively.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She proceeded to head overseas and fulfilled a Diploma in Education and an MA degree from the [[University of London]] between 1978 and 1979.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /><ref name=\"timeslive1604\">{{cite news |title=Higher education's Naledi Pandor caps string of qualifications with doctorate |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-04-16-higher-educations-naledi-pandor-caps-string-of-qualifications-with-doctorate/ |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nPandir obtained a Diploma in Higher Education, Administration and Leadership from Bryn Mawr Summer Programme in 1992, and soon enrolled at the [[Kennedy School of Government]] to receive a Diploma in Leadership in Development in 1997. She also attained an MA degree in Linguistics from the [[University of Stellenbosch]] in the same year.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> Pandor received her PhD in Education at the [[University of Pretoria]] in 2019, with a thesis titled \"The contested meaning of transformation in higher education in post-apartheid South Africa\".<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Petersen |first1=Tammy |title=Minister Pandor walks the walk, graduating with PhD in Education |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/minister-pandor-walks-the-walk-graduating-with-phd-in-education-20190416 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=LOOK: 'She continues to inspire us': Naledi Pandor awarded PhD |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/look-she-continues-to-inspire-us-naledi-pandor-awarded-phd-21444274 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=16 April 2019 |location=Pretoria, Gauteng}}</ref>\n\n==Teaching career==\nPandor became a teacher at the Ernest Bevin School in [[London]] in 1980. She was soon employed as a teacher in [[Gaborone]] in 1981 and worked as one until 1984. She proceeded to serve as an instructor at the Taung College of Education from 1984 to 1986. Pandor worked as a senior lecturer in English at the [[University of Bophuthatswana]] from 1986 to 1989. She soon worked as a senior fellow in the Academic Support Programme of the [[University of Cape Town]] between 1989 and 1994.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nWhile at the University of Bophuthatswana, Pandor served as the chair of the university's Union of Democratic Staff Associations between 1988 and 1990. She was appointed the chairperson of the Western Cape National Executive Committee of the National Education Coordinating Committee in 1991 and served in the position until 1993. At the same time, she was part of the ANC's Western Cape Education Committee.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nAdditionally, Pandor chaired the ANC Athlone Central branch, whilst serving as both the head of the Desmond Tutu Education Trust and the Western Cape School Building Trust.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nDuring 1992 and 1995, she worked as deputy head of the Tertiary Education Fund of South Africa. She soon became head of the fund. She was also deputy chairperson of the Joint Education Trust Board of Trustees between 1993 and 2001.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nShe was chancellor of Cape Technikon from 2002 to 2004. During the same period, she was a member of the governing council of the [[University of Fort Hare]].<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n[[File:Naledi Pandor 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Pandor at the opening exhibition of the German-South African Science Year in Cape Town in 2012]]\nPandor became a Member of the Parliament in the lower house of Parliament, the [[National Assembly of South Africa|National Assembly]], following the [[1994 South African general election|1994 general election]].<ref name=\"encaex\">{{cite news |title=EXPLAINER: Who is Naledi Pandor? |url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/who-is-naledi-pandor |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=6 November 2017}}</ref> Within the ANC caucus, she served as Deputy Chief Whip from 1995 until her deployment to the upper house of Parliament, the [[National Council of Provinces]], in 1998. She served as Deputy Chairperson until her appointment as Chairperson following the [[1999 South African general election|1999 general election]]. She succeeded inaugural Chairperson [[Mosioua Lekota]] when she assumed the office on 21 June 1999. She was the first woman to hold the role. [[Joyce Kgoali]] succeeded Pandor in 2004 and consequently became the second woman to hold the role.<ref name=\"encaex\" />\n\nPandor returned to the National Assembly following the [[2004 South African general election|2004 general election]]. President [[Thabo Mbeki]] appointed her to the role of [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]. She took office on 12 May 2004.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mbeki's cabinet list |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Mbekis-cabinet-list-20040428 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=28 April 2004}}</ref> During her tenure in the portfolio, she was responsible for a complete overhaul of the nation's education system. Pandor initiated reforms to the country's failed implementation of the [[outcomes-based education]] (OBE) system.<ref>{{cite news |title=Own-language schooling, for free |url=https://www.brandsouthafrica.com/governance/education/curriculum-180505 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Brand South Africa |date=18 May 2005}}</ref> Mbeki resigned in 2008 and left [[Kgalema Motlanthe]] in charge. Motlanthe retained Pandor in her position in his interim cabinet.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Motlanthe sworn in as interim president |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2008-09-25-motlanthe-sworn-in-as-interim-president |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=25 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=President Motlanthe\u2019s new cabinet |url=https://www.brandsouthafrica.com/governance/developmentnews/cabinet260908 |website=Brand South Africa |accessdate=24 September 2019|date=26 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Harsh Vardhan with the Vice Minister for Science, Technology and Innovation of Brazil, Mr. \u00c1lvaro Toubes Prata, the Deputy Minister of Federation of Russia, Mr. Alexey Lopatia (1).jpg|thumb|Pandor and her ministerial counterparts at the 4th BRICS Science & Technology Ministers Meeting in 2016]]\nFollowing the [[2009 South African general election|2009 general election]], Jacob Zuma became the new President of South Africa. He unbundled the Education Ministry into two new portfolios and appointed Pandor to the newly-established post of [[Minister of Science and Technology]] in May 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rossouw |first1=Mandy |title=Zuma's Cabinet: Those who didn't make the cut |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-10-zumas-cabinet-those-who-didnt-make-the-cut |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=10 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=South Africa Cabinet Members 2009 to 2010 |url=https://www.sahistory.org.za/article/south-africa-cabinet-members-2009-2010 |website=South African History Online |accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref> During her time in the position, Pandor served as a driving force for South Africa to host the [[Square Kilometre Array]] (SKA) in the Karoo region. South Africa won the bid.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tshivhidzo |first1=Edwin |title=SA will win bid to host SKA - Pandor |url=https://www.sanews.gov.za/south-africa/sa-will-win-bid-host-ska-pandor |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=SA News |date=31 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Richard |title=South Africa eyes SKA telescope with bated breath |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-02-15-south-africa-eyes-ska-telescope-with-bated-breath |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=15 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=President Zuma congratulates Minister of Science and Technology on winning the bid to host the SKA |url=https://www.gov.za/president-zuma-congratulates-minister-science-and-technology-winning-bid-host-ska |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=South African Government |date=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]] resigned as [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]] in order for her to take up the role as [[African Union|Chair of the African Union]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maasho |first1=Aaron |title=Dlamini-Zuma elected to head AU Commission |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-07-16-dlamini-zuma-elected-to-head-au-commission |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=16 July 2012}}</ref> Her resignation caused a vacancy in the cabinet. President Zuma consequently appointed Pandor as Minister of Home Affairs in an acting capacity on 2 October 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pandor appointed acting home affairs minister |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-10-02-pandor-appointed-acting-home-affairs-minister |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=2 October 2012}}</ref> Soon after on 4 October 2012, Zuma formally appointed her as Minister of Home Affairs.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Maharaj |first1=Mac |title=Naledi Pandor appointed Home Affairs minister - Presidency |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/naledi-pandor-appointed-home-affairs-minister--pre |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=3 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing her re-election in the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general election]], President Zuma announced that Pandor would return to the [[Department of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Department of Science and Technology]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Complete list of cabinet ministers |url=https://www.enca.com/elections-2014-information/president-jacob-zuma-announces-his-cabinet |accessdate=24 September 2014 |newspaper=eNCA |date=25 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Zuma shakes things up with new Cabinet |url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/zuma-shakes-things-new-cabinet |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=25 May 2014}}</ref> [[Malusi Gigaba]] succeeded her as Minister of Home Affairs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peyper |first1=Lindsey |title=Gigaba in hot seat as new Finance Minister |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/gigaba-in-hot-seat-as-new-finance-minister-20170331|newspaper=News24 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |date=31 March 2017}}</ref> She took office on 26 May 2014 and succeeded [[Derek Hanekom]].<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Quintal |first1=Genevieve |title=Marathon swearing-in for Zuma\u2019s Cabinet |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/marathon-swearing-in-for-zumas-cabinet-1694171 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Zuma names new cabinet |url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2014-05-26-zuma-names-new-cabinet/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=SowetanLIVE |date=26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Cyril Ramaphosa]] assumed the office of President in February 2018. Pandor was appointed [[Minister of Higher Education and Training]] and took office on 27 February 2018, succeeding [[Hlengiwe Mkhize]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rabkin |first1=Franny |last2=Pather |first2=Ra'eesa |title=New deputy president, finance minister announced in major Cabinet reshuffle |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-02-26-ramaphosa-cabinet-reshuffle-february-2018 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=26 February 2018 |quote=Minister of Higher education - Naledi Pandor}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Who is in and who is out: Ramaphosa's Cabinet reshuffle |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/who-is-in-and-who-is-out-ramaphosas-cabinet-reshuffle-20180226 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=26 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=IN FULL Ramaphosa hires and fires - read his Cabinet reshuffle speech |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-02-26-in-full--ramaphosa-hires-and-fires-read-his-cabinet-reshuffle-speech/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2019 South African general election|2019 general election]], the Ministry of Higher Education and Training was split. Pandor was speculated to be appointed [[Deputy President of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Dlamini-Zuma, Pandor tipped to become deputy president |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/dlamini-zuma-pandor-tipped-to-become-deputy-president-20190522 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=22 May 2019}}</ref> She was President Ramaphosa's original choice for Deputy President back in 2017 at the [[54th National Conference of the African National Congress|ANC's elective conference]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicolson |first1=Greg |title=#ANCdecides2017: The Top Six that could have been |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-12-18-ancdecides2017-the-top-six-that-could-have-been/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=18 December 2017}}</ref> She was instead appointed [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]] and assumed the post on 30 May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Introducing the executives Cyril Ramaphosa has chosen to serve SA |url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-05-30-the-men-and-women-cyril-ramaphosa-has-chosen-to-serve-sa/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=BusinessDay |date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPandor is married to Sharif Joseph Pandor, whom she met while studying in [[Botswana]], and they have four children together, Fazlur, Aisha, Suraya and Haroon. She converted to [[Islam]] after she met her husband. Her in-laws gave her the Islamic name of Nadia. On her religious conversion, Pandor said: \"My parents said God is God. As long as you worship Him we will support you and the Islamic principles are universal. Certainly, Islam demands much more of you in terms of observance.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Humble and willing to learn: Naledi Pandor is leading by example |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2019-05-19-humble-and-willing-to-learn-naledi-pandor-is-leading-by-example/ |newspaper=The Sunday Times |accessdate=23 September 2019 |date=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Naledi Pandor}}\n* {{People's Assembly (South Africa)|grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor|Naledi Pandor}}\n* [https://www.sahistory.org.za/people/grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor \u2013 South African History Online]\n* [https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor-ms Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor, Ms \u2013 South African Government]\n* [http://www.dirco.gov.za/department/profile_pandor.html  Profile: Dr Naledi Pandor, Minister \u2013 Dirco]\n* [https://www.dst.gov.za/index.php/media-room/20-temp/organogram/218-naledi-pandor-biography Naledi Pandor Biographical notes \u2013 dst.gov.za]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lindiwe Sisulu]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hlengiwe Mkhize]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Ministry split''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Derek Hanekom]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nkhensani Kubayi-Ngubane]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]]|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Malusi Gigaba]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mosibudi Mangena]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]|years=2009\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Derek Hanekom]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kader Asmal]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]|years=2004\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Ministry split''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mosiuoa Lekota]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[National Council of Provinces|Chairperson of the National Council of Provinces]]|years=1999\u20132004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Joyce Kgoali]]}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{SouthAfricaSenateNCOPPresidents}}\n{{G20-Foreign}}\n{{Thabo Mbeki cabinet 2}}\n{{Kgalema Motlanthe cabinet 1}}\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 1}}\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pandor, Naledi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Education ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Home Affairs of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Chairpersons of the National Council of Provinces]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Stellenbosch University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Eswatini alumni]]\n[[Category:South African Muslims]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam]]\n[[Category:People from Durban]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses with Star and Sash of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Female foreign ministers]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of South Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTeaching career:Fixes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naledi_Pandor"}
{"title_page": "Unauthorized Freud", "text_new": "{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name = Unauthorized Freud: Doubters Confront a Legend\n| image = File:Unauthorized Freud.jpg\n| caption = Cover of the first edition\n| editor = [[Frederick Crews]]\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| subject = [[Sigmund Freud]]\n| publisher = [[Viking Press|Viking Penguin]]\n| pub_date = 1998\n| media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]])\n| pages = 352\n| isbn = 978-0670872213\n}}\n'''''Unauthorized Freud: Doubters Confront a Legend''''' is a 1998 book about [[Sigmund Freud]], the founder of [[psychoanalysis]], edited by the critic [[Frederick Crews]]. The book received both positive reviews, crediting Crews with having assembled a coherent case against Freud's theories and therapeutic techniques, and more mixed evaluations, which criticized Crews for lacking objectivity.\n\n==Summary==\n''Unauthorized Freud'' is a collection of critical articles about [[Sigmund Freud]] and [[psychoanalysis]]. In addition to Crews, the contributors include the critic [[Stanley Fish]], the historians [[David Stannard]] and [[Peter Swales (historian)|Peter Swales]], the philologist [[Sebastiano Timpanaro]], the philosophers [[Mikkel Borch-Jacobsen]], [[Frank Cioffi]], Barbara Von Eckardt, [[Ernest Gellner]], and [[Adolf Gr\u00fcnbaum]], the psychiatrist [[Joseph Wolpe]], the psychoanalyst Rosemarie Sand, and the psychologists Malcolm Macmillan, [[Stanley Rachman]], and [[Frank Sulloway]]. The remaining contributors are Allen Esterson, Fran\u00e7ois Roustang, John Farrell, and Lavinia Edmunds. In his preface, Crews states that the book's purpose is to reevaluate Freud and examine psychoanalysis as a science and that it was composed primarily for \"the general reader\". Though writing that it shows psychoanalysis \"to have been a mistake that grew into an imposture\", he observes that it represents a range of different views, some more critical of Freud and psychoanalysis than others. Crews also writes that all of the features of [[recovered-memory therapy]] were pioneered by Freud, and that it is an example of the harmful influence of psychoanalysis.{{sfn|Crews|1999|pages=ix\u2013277}}\n\nThe contribution from Sulloway is an extract from ''[[Freud, Biologist of the Mind]]'' (1979), while that from Gr\u00fcnbaum is an extract from ''[[The Foundations of Psychoanalysis]]'' (1984), and that of Macmillan is an extract from ''[[Freud Evaluated]]'' (1991).{{sfn|Crews|1999|pages=54, 76, 129}}\n\n==Publication history==\n''Unauthorized Freud'' was first published in 1998 by [[Viking Press|Viking Penguin]]. In 1999, it was published by [[Penguin Books]].{{sfn|Crews|1999|page=vi}}\n\n==Reception==\n''Unauthorized Freud'' received positive reviews from Thomas T. Lewis in ''Magill Book Reviews'' and Edward T. Oakes in ''[[First Things]]'',{{sfn|Lewis|1999}}{{sfn|Oakes|1999|pages=38\u201342}} as well as from ''[[Publishers Weekly]]''.{{sfn|''Publishers Weekly''|1998|page=76}} The book received mixed reviews from Adam Bresnick in ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'',{{sfn|Bresnick|1998|pages=11\u201312}} Edward V. Stein in ''Pastoral Psychology'',{{sfn|Stein|1999|pages=317\u2013318}} and Kurt Jacobsen in ''Psychoanalytic Studies''.{{sfn|Jacobsen|2000|pages=403\u2013404}} The book was also reviewed by Mary Carroll in ''[[Booklist]]'',{{sfn|Carroll|1998|page=1833}} [[Mark Bauerlein]] in ''[[Skeptical Inquirer]]'',{{sfn|Bauerlein|1999|pages=51\u201352}} the critic [[Carol Iannone]] in ''[[Telos (journal)|Telos]]'',{{sfn|Iannone|1999|pages=164\u2013168}} and the psychiatrist [[David Healy (psychiatrist)|David Healy]] in ''[[The BMJ]]''.{{sfn|Healy|1999|page=949}}\n\nLewis described the selections included in the book as \"impressive\". He considered the most interesting contributions to be the \"critical evaluations of Freud's case studies\". He concluded that while some contributions were \"unnecessarily polemical\", they \"add up to a devastating indictment of Freud's theories and therapeutic methods.\"{{sfn|Lewis|1999}} Oakes credited Crews with presenting a detailed case against Freud, writing that it \"would convince all but the most doctrinaire Freudian\", and with showing the links between psychoanalysis and the recovered memory movement. He believed that the contributions it contained made effective criticisms of Freud's use of \"evidence gained in hypnosis and free association\", his \"rewriting of the history of the psychoanalytic movement\", and \"his lazy neurological assumption that infants have brains developed enough to sustain the emotional trauma he attributes to them\". He described the work as \"engrossing\" and \"absorbing and consistently well-argued\".{{sfn|Oakes|1999|pages=38\u201342}}\n\n''Publishers Weekly'' wrote that the essays included in the book presented a \"formidable critique\" of both Freudian theory and practice and Freud's major cases, and credited its contributors with presenting \"compelling evidence that Freud habitually and greatly exaggerated his therapeutic successes\" and with casting serious doubt on \"confidence in free association as a curative tool to decipher the meaning of dreams or to reconstruct events from a patient's distant past.\" While it wrote that the book overstated the case against Freud, it praised the work Crews did in editing it, concluding that he had shaped the selections into a \"cohesive whole\" and \"put psychoanalysis squarely on the defensive.\"{{sfn|''Publishers Weekly''|1998|page=76}}\n\nBresnick was unconvinced by the book's case against Freud, but nevertheless believed it had redeeming value. He praised the contribution by Swales.{{sfn|Bresnick|1998|pages=11\u201312}} Stein described the book as a \"devastatingly critical assault\" on Freud and psychoanalysis and predicted that it would have a lasting impact. He credited its contributors with showing \"the fragility of the classical case studies, the circularity of much of Freud's logic and the degree of Freud's identification with favorable outcomes.\" However, he wrote that it was also malicious, lacking in objectivity, uneven in quality, and showed a lack of appreciation for the opposition Freud had to face and insensitivity toward Freud's inner conflicts. He also observed that only a minority of the contributors had a professional background in psychology of therapy.{{sfn|Stein|1999|pages=317\u2013318}} Jacobsen believed that some of the essays made legitimate criticisms of psychoanalysis. However, he criticized Crews for lacking objectivity and fair-mindedness and rejected his claim that Freud was responsible for the \"repressed memory movement.\"{{sfn|Jacobsen|2000|pages=403\u2013404}}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Freud and Philosophy]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n;Books\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Crews|first1=Frederick, Editor |title=Unauthorized Freud: Doubters Confront a Legend |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=New York |year=1999 |isbn=0-14-028017-0 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Journals\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |title=The Freud Controversy at Century's End |last1=Bauerlein|first1=Mark |journal=[[Skeptical Inquirer]] |volume=23 |issue=5 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=The originality of listening |last1=Bresnick|first1=Adam |journal=[[The Times Literary Supplement]] |volume= |issue=4987 |year=1998 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Adult books: Nonfiction |last1=Carroll|first1=Mary |journal=[[Booklist]] |volume=94 |issue=21-22 |year=1998 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Reviews |last1=Healy|first1=David |journal=[[The BMJ]] |volume=318 |issue=7188 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Reconsidering Freud |last1=Iannone|first1=Carol |journal=[[Telos (journal)|Telos]] |volume= |issue=116 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Reviews |last1=Jacobsen|first1=Kurt |journal=Psychoanalytic Studies |volume=2 |issue=4 |year=2000 |doi=10.1080/14608950020005749 |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Unauthorized Freud: Doubters confront a Legend |last1=Lewis|first1=Thomas T. |journal=Magill Book Reviews |volume= |issue=August 1 1999 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=The Man Behind the Curtain |last1=Oakes|first1=Edward T. |journal=[[First Things]] |volume= |issue=89 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Book Reviews |last1=Stein|first1=Edward V. |journal=Pastoral Psychology |volume=47 |issue=4 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Forecasts: Nonfiction |journal=[[Publishers Weekly]] |volume=245 |issue=25 |year=1998 |doi= |ref={{harvid|Publishers Weekly|1998}}}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:1998 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books about Sigmund Freud]]\n[[Category:Books by Frederick Crews]]\n[[Category:English-language books]]\n[[Category:Viking Press books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name = Unauthorized Freud: Doubters Confront a Legend\n| image = File:Unauthorized Freud.jpg\n| caption = Cover of the first edition\n| editor = [[Frederick Crews]]\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| subject = [[Sigmund Freud]]\n| publisher = [[Viking Press|Viking Penguin]]\n| pub_date = 1998\n| media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]])\n| pages = 352\n| isbn = 978-0670872213\n}}\n'''''Unauthorized Freud: Doubters Confront a Legend''''' is a 1998 book about [[Sigmund Freud]], the founder of [[psychoanalysis]], edited by the critic [[Frederick Crews]]. The book received both positive reviews, crediting Crews with having assembled a coherent case against Freud's theories and therapeutic techniques, and more mixed evaluations, which criticized Crews for lacking objectivity.\n\n==Summary==\n''Unauthorized Freud'' is a collection of critical articles about [[Sigmund Freud]] and [[psychoanalysis]]. In addition to Crews, the contributors include the critic [[Stanley Fish]], the historians [[David Stannard]] and [[Peter Swales (historian)|Peter Swales]], the philologist [[Sebastiano Timpanaro]], the philosophers [[Mikkel Borch-Jacobsen]], [[Frank Cioffi]], Barbara Von Eckardt, [[Ernest Gellner]], and [[Adolf Gr\u00fcnbaum]], the psychiatrist [[Joseph Wolpe]], the psychoanalyst Rosemarie Sand, and the psychologists Malcolm Macmillan, [[Stanley Rachman]], and [[Frank Sulloway]]. The remaining contributors are Allen Esterson, Fran\u00e7ois Roustang, John Farrell, and Lavinia Edmunds. In his preface, Crews states that the book's purpose is to reevaluate Freud and examine psychoanalysis as a science and that it was composed primarily for \"the general reader\". Though writing that it shows psychoanalysis \"to have been a mistake that grew into an imposture\", he observes that it represents a range of different views, some more critical of Freud and psychoanalysis than others. Crews also writes that all of the features of [[recovered-memory therapy]] were pioneered by Freud, and that it is an example of the harmful influence of psychoanalysis.{{sfn|Crews|1999|pages=ix\u2013277}}\n\nThe contribution from Sulloway is an extract from ''[[Freud, Biologist of the Mind]]'' (1979), while that from Gr\u00fcnbaum is an extract from ''[[The Foundations of Psychoanalysis]]'' (1984), and that of Macmillan is an extract from ''[[Freud Evaluated]]'' (1991).{{sfn|Crews|1999|pages=54, 76, 129}}\n\n==Publication history==\n''Unauthorized Freud'' was first published in 1998 by [[Viking Press|Viking Penguin]]. In 1999, it was published by [[Penguin Books]].{{sfn|Crews|1999|page=vi}}\n\n==Reception==\n''Unauthorized Freud'' received positive reviews from Thomas T. Lewis in ''Magill Book Reviews'' and Edward T. Oakes in ''[[First Things]]'',{{sfn|Lewis|1999}}{{sfn|Oakes|1999|pages=38\u201342}} as well as from ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'',{{sfn|''Publishers Weekly''|1998|page=76}}. The book received mixed reviews from Adam Bresnick in ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'',{{sfn|Bresnick|1998|pages=11\u201312}} Edward V. Stein in ''Pastoral Psychology'',{{sfn|Stein|1999|pages=317\u2013318}} and Kurt Jacobsen in ''Psychoanalytic Studies''.{{sfn|Jacobsen|2000|pages=403\u2013404}} The book was also reviewed by Mary Carroll in ''[[Booklist]]'',{{sfn|Carroll|1998|page=1833}} [[Mark Bauerlein]] in ''[[Skeptical Inquirer]]'',{{sfn|Bauerlein|1999|pages=51\u201352}} the critic [[Carol Iannone]] in ''[[Telos (journal)|Telos]]'',{{sfn|Iannone|1999|pages=164\u2013168}} and the psychiatrist [[David Healy (psychiatrist)|David Healy]] in ''[[The BMJ]]''.{{sfn|Healy|1999|page=949}}\n\nLewis described the selections included in the book as \"impressive\". He considered the most interesting contributions to be the \"critical evaluations of Freud's case studies\". He concluded that while some contributions were \"unnecessarily polemical\", they \"add up to a devastating indictment of Freud's theories and therapeutic methods.\"{{sfn|Lewis|1999}} Oakes credited Crews with presenting a detailed case against Freud, writing that it \"would convince all but the most doctrinaire Freudian\", and with showing the links between psychoanalysis and the recovered memory movement. He believed that the contributions it contained made effective criticisms of Freud's use of \"evidence gained in hypnosis and free association\", his \"rewriting of the history of the psychoanalytic movement\", and \"his lazy neurological assumption that infants have brains developed enough to sustain the emotional trauma he attributes to them\". He described the work as \"engrossing\" and \"absorbing and consistently well-argued\".{{sfn|Oakes|1999|pages=38\u201342}}\n\n''Publishers Weekly'' wrote that the essays included in the book presented a \"formidable critique\" of both Freudian theory and practice and Freud's major cases, and credited its contributors with presenting \"compelling evidence that Freud habitually and greatly exaggerated his therapeutic successes\" and with casting serious doubt on \"confidence in free association as a curative tool to decipher the meaning of dreams or to reconstruct events from a patient's distant past.\" While it wrote that the book overstated the case against Freud, it praised the work Crews did in editing it, concluding that he had shaped the selections into a \"cohesive whole\" and \"put psychoanalysis squarely on the defensive.\"{{sfn|''Publishers Weekly''|1998|page=76}}\n\nBresnick was unconvinced by the book's case against Freud, but nevertheless believed it had redeeming value. He praised the contribution by Swales.{{sfn|Bresnick|1998|pages=11\u201312}} Stein described the book as a \"devastatingly critical assault\" on Freud and psychoanalysis and predicted that it would have a lasting impact. He credited its contributors with showing \"the fragility of the classical case studies, the circularity of much of Freud's logic and the degree of Freud's identification with favorable outcomes.\" However, he wrote that it was also malicious, lacking in objectivity, uneven in quality, and showed a lack of appreciation for the opposition Freud had to face and insensitivity toward Freud's inner conflicts. He also observed that only a minority of the contributors had a professional background in psychology of therapy.{{sfn|Stein|1999|pages=317\u2013318}} Jacobsen believed that some of the essays made legitimate criticisms of psychoanalysis. However, he criticized Crews for lacking objectivity and fair-mindedness and rejected his claim that Freud was responsible for the \"repressed memory movement.\"{{sfn|Jacobsen|2000|pages=403\u2013404}}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Freud and Philosophy]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n;Books\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Crews|first1=Frederick, Editor |title=Unauthorized Freud: Doubters Confront a Legend |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=New York |year=1999 |isbn=0-14-028017-0 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Journals\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |title=The Freud Controversy at Century's End |last1=Bauerlein|first1=Mark |journal=[[Skeptical Inquirer]] |volume=23 |issue=5 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=The originality of listening |last1=Bresnick|first1=Adam |journal=[[The Times Literary Supplement]] |volume= |issue=4987 |year=1998 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Adult books: Nonfiction |last1=Carroll|first1=Mary |journal=[[Booklist]] |volume=94 |issue=21-22 |year=1998 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Reviews |last1=Healy|first1=David |journal=[[The BMJ]] |volume=318 |issue=7188 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Reconsidering Freud |last1=Iannone|first1=Carol |journal=[[Telos (journal)|Telos]] |volume= |issue=116 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Reviews |last1=Jacobsen|first1=Kurt |journal=Psychoanalytic Studies |volume=2 |issue=4 |year=2000 |doi=10.1080/14608950020005749 |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Unauthorized Freud: Doubters confront a Legend |last1=Lewis|first1=Thomas T. |journal=Magill Book Reviews |volume= |issue=August 1 1999 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=The Man Behind the Curtain |last1=Oakes|first1=Edward T. |journal=[[First Things]] |volume= |issue=89 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Book Reviews |last1=Stein|first1=Edward V. |journal=Pastoral Psychology |volume=47 |issue=4 |year=1999 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Forecasts: Nonfiction |journal=[[Publishers Weekly]] |volume=245 |issue=25 |year=1998 |doi= |ref={{harvid|Publishers Weekly|1998}}}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:1998 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books about Sigmund Freud]]\n[[Category:Books by Frederick Crews]]\n[[Category:English-language books]]\n[[Category:Viking Press books]]\n", "name_user": "Freeknowledgecreator", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:correct punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unauthorized_Freud"}
{"title_page": "Midland Community Unit School District", "text_new": "'''Midland Community Unit School District #7''' is a school district headquartered in [[Sparland, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.midland-7.net/|title=Home|publisher=Midland Community Unit School District #7|accessdate=2020-03-29|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIt operates Midland Elementary School, Midland Middle School, and [[Midland High School (Illinois)|Midland High School]].\n\n==History==\n{{expand section|date=March 2020}}\nThe district formed through an act of consolidation circa 1996. Rolf Sivertsen served as the Midland CUSD superintendent until July 1, 2016 as he moved to [[Canton, Illinois]].<ref name=Smithnewsuper2016>{{cite web|author=Smith, Gary L.|url=https://www.pjstar.com/article/20160517/NEWS/160519447|title=Midland School Boad selects Fairfield principal Bill Wrenn as superintendent|work=[[Peoria Journal Star|Journal Star]]|date=2016-05-17|accessdate=2020-03-29|quote=Sivertsen, [...] will be trying to heal the sometimes bitter geographic divisions in the approximately 20-year-old consolidated district.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Gary L. Smith of the ''[[Peoria Journal Star|Journal Star]]'' wrote that there were \"sometimes bitter geographic divisions\" and cited a case where, in an election to build a new school in [[Lacon, Illinois|Lacon]], residents of Lacon gave \"overwhelming support\" but that people in Sparland and [[Varna, Illinois|Varna]] \"strongly opposed\" the measure.<ref name=Smithnewsuper2016/> Overall 55% of participants voted in favor in 2016, causing the measure to pass.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pekintimes.com/news/20160315/referendum-for-new-midland-school-in-lacon-passes-by-about-55|title=Referendum for new Midland school in Lacon passes by about 55%|work=[[Pekin Daily Times]]|date=2016-03-15|accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2016 L. William \"Bill\" Wrenn<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pitchfordfuneralhome.com/obituaries/L-William-Bill--Wrenn?obId=10734266|title=L. William \"Bill Wrenn|publisher=Pitchford Funeral Home|accessdate=2020-03-29}} - [https://www.centralillinoisproud.com/news/midland-community-superintendent-dies-over-the-weekend-district-has-support-staff-on-hand-this-week/ Linked from this news article]</ref> was selected as the superintendent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centralillinoisproud.com/news/midland-community-superintendent-dies-over-the-weekend-district-has-support-staff-on-hand-this-week/|title=Midland Community superintendent dies over the weekend, district has support staff on hand this week|work=[[CBS]] Central Illinois Proud news station|date=2020-01-27|accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref> Wrenn served in this capacity until he died in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|author=Shelley, Tim|url=https://www.wglt.org/post/midland-superintendent-dies-over-weekend#stream/0|title=Midland Superintendent Dies Over the Weekend |work=[[WGLT]]|date=2020-01-27|accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref> Wrenn planned to finish his term at the end of the 2019\u20132020 school year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Smith, Gary L.|url=https://www.pjstar.com/news/20200127/midland-school-district-superintendent-died-over-weekend|title=Midland School District superintendent died over the weekend|work=[[Peoria Journal Star|Journal Star]]|date=2020-01-27|accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.midland-7.net/ Midland Community Unit School District #7]\n\n[[Category:School districts in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Education in Marshall County, Illinois]]\n\n\n{{Illinois-school-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Midland Community Unit School District #7''' is a school district headquartered in [[Sparland, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.midland-7.net/|title=Home|publisher=Midland Community Unit School District #7|accessdate=2020-03-29|quote=}}</ref>\n\nIt operates Midland Elementary School, Midland Middle School, and [[Midland High School (Illinois)|Midland High School]].\n\n==History==\n{{expand section|date=March 2020}}\nThe district formed through an act of consolidation circa 1996. Rolf Sivertsen served as the Midland CUSD superintendent until July 1, 2016 as he moved to [[Canton, Illinois]].<ref name=Smithnewsuper2016>{{cite web|author=Smith, Gary L.|url=https://www.pjstar.com/article/20160517/NEWS/160519447|title=Midland School Boad selects Fairfield principal Bill Wrenn as superintendent|work=[[Journal Star]]|date=2016-05-17|accessdate=2020-03-29|quote=Sivertsen, [...] will be trying to heal the sometimes bitter geographic divisions in the approximately 20-year-old consolidated district.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Gary L. Smith of the ''[[Journal Star]]'' wrote that there were \"sometimes bitter geographic divisions\" and cited a case where, in an election to build a new school in [[Lacon, Illinois|Lacon]], residents of Lacon gave \"overwhelming support\" but that people in Sparland and [[Varna, Illinois|Varna]] \"strongly opposed\" the measure.<ref name=Smithnewsuper2016/> Overall 55% of participants voted in favor in 2016, causing the measure to pass.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pekintimes.com/news/20160315/referendum-for-new-midland-school-in-lacon-passes-by-about-55|title=Referendum for new Midland school in Lacon passes by about 55%|work=[[Pekin Daily Times]]|date=2016-03-15|accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2016 L. William \"Bill\" Wrenn<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pitchfordfuneralhome.com/obituaries/L-William-Bill--Wrenn?obId=10734266|title=L. William \"Bill Wrenn|publisher=Pitchford Funeral Home|accessdate=2020-03-29}} - [https://www.centralillinoisproud.com/news/midland-community-superintendent-dies-over-the-weekend-district-has-support-staff-on-hand-this-week/ Linked from this news article]</ref> was selected as the superintendent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centralillinoisproud.com/news/midland-community-superintendent-dies-over-the-weekend-district-has-support-staff-on-hand-this-week/|title=Midland Community superinte